The lex Aelia Sentia did not apply to peregrini, to whom, however, this part of it relating to manumission in fraud of creditore was extended by a ‘senatusconsultum' under Hadrian ; Gaius i. 47. Gaius says (i. 37) that the statute allowed a patron to revoke manumissione by bis freedmen which would seriously impair bis own rights of succession. For the sale of a deceased insolvent’s property see Gaius iii. 78-80: ir entailed posthumous infamia, whence it is said ‘servus necessarius.. . non magis patrimonium quam infamiam consequi videtur' Cod.
